Great Leader's Revival
The Battle of Waterloo has been over for two centuries now, and Napoleon's disastrous defeat in it has severely damaged France's pride to such an extent that General de Gaulle did not even mention it in his writing of French military history.
Despite this, if you admit that "greatness" is a personal quality, then Napoleon and de Gaulle could both be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader".
In Marx's view, France's class struggle created an environment in which a strange mediocrity like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was hardly an exceptional general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon is great or not, we should clarify whether anyone can be described as great.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that a great leader must meet two particularly important standards.
First, can this leader grasp the historical trend?
Otto von Bismarck did so, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "rustle of the divine cloak."
Second, has this leader made an important decision?
Of course, if the leader is forced to make a decision, he or she cannot be blamed for it, nor can he or she be credited for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether leaders have the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make correct decisions on behalf of the country.
Charles de Gaulle therefore deservedly deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-war relegation zone.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressed two attempted coups, ended the Algerian War, and drafted the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, Charles de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their status in the post-war global order.
In fact, de Gaulle and Churchill's ultimate impact on establishing their respective world views is somewhat exaggerated.
Their successors years later still viewed the world - and their country's role in it - through the lens of discussing and distorting rationality, and the constraints.
The result is that the leaders of the two countries have never since been able to achieve achievements comparable to those of the two great leaders.
But there was one British prime minister who could rival her: Margaret Thatcher, a highly divisive figure with as many people who liked her as those who disliked her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to her own cabinet and party's opposition activities.
But not everyone's approval is needed to become a great leader.
In reality, even Margaret Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
Besides being the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, she was almost the first female Prime Minister of other countries in the world, and Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic recession.
Not only that, the assault she launched against the over-powerful labor union enhanced its manageability at a time when the country seemed to be slipping into chaos and turmoil.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for the "Great Leader".
Similarly, far from being flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China also deserves to be a great leader.
Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square Massacre, in addition to assisting Mao in doing evil.
But Deng also stimulated the market, allowing China to embark on a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that would ultimately lift hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people believe that Singapore's founding father and long-time Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew was a very great man, although he may have aspired to a bigger stage.
In fact, the size of the country does not seem to affect a person from becoming a great leader.
I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce great leaders without any derogatory intent, especially given the country's relatively low-key political climate.
The United States is vast enough to be the birthplace of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight D. Eisenhower – though not intellectual giants – showed remarkable perceptiveness in establishing the post-war international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, have possessed extremely high gifts – the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was a man of many talents.
He completed a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His talents were unmatched and inspirational; in fact, his assassination only reinforced the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one can be considered a great figure until after Mandela's death, Mandela embodied courage, authority and magnanimity with elegance.
In fact, he is the most captivating and charming leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either Africans or African Americans.
So, what's the matter today?
The only person who is qualified to call herself great is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first, but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Angela Merkel formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin when he invaded Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on immigration.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders - are the exercisers of political power - can alter the situation, whether it becomes better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, she has shown the direction for Europe to cope with the high-level survival crisis.
